    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>SEWER DISTRICTS CRITICIZED</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <byline class="print_byline">By ROBERT WORTH</byline>
      <byline class="normalized_byline">Worth, Robert</byline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Westchester County League of Women Voters reports, after 18-month-study, that leaky sewer pipes, failing septic systems and overflows from sewage treatment plants are threatening New York City watershed and Long Island Sound and calls for better enforcment of existing laws (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>Leaky sewer pipes, failing septic systems and overflows from sewage treatment plants are among the dangers listed in a report by the Westchester County League of Women Voters. The product of an 18-month study, the report warns that the county's sewage problems are a threat to the New York City watershed and Long Island Sound, and calls for better enforcement of existing laws. The report also calls for greater equity in sewer rates across the county. ''Somebody has to take the lead role in ensuring that these things are done,'' Roberta Wiernik, the league's president, said.</p>
        <p>ROBERT WORTH</p>
      </block>
